In a German General Staff publication, it was written that "Germany had been brought near to certain destruction ({{lang|de|''sicheren Untergang''}}) by the Flanders battle of 1917".{{sfn|Edmonds |1948|p=xiii}} In his Memoirs of 1938, Lloyd George wrote, "Passchendaele was indeed one of the greatest disasters of the war&nbsp;... No soldier of any intelligence now defends this senseless campaign&nbsp;...".{{sfn|Terraine|1977|pp=xix–xx}} In 1939, G. C. Wynne wrote that the British had eventually reached Passchendaele Ridge and captured {{lang|de|''Flandern I Stellung''}}; beyond them were {{lang|de|''Flandern II''}} and {{lang|de|''Flandern III''}} (which was nearly complete). The German submarine bases on the coast had not been captured but the objective of diverting the Germans from the French further south, while they recovered from the Nivelle Offensive of April, had succeeded.{{sfn|Wynne|1939|pp=214–215}}

In 1997, Griffith wrote that the ''bite and hold'' system kept moving until November, because the BEF had developed a workable system of offensive tactics, against which the Germans ultimately had no answer.{{sfn|Liddle|1997|p=71}} A decade later, Sheldon wrote that relative casualty figures were irrelevant, because the German army could not afford great numbers of losses or to lose the initiative, by being compelled to fight another defensive battle on ground of the Allies' choosing. The Third Battle of Ypres pinned the German army to Flanders and caused unsustainable casualties.{{sfn|Sheldon|2007|pp=313–317}} At a conference on 13 October, a scheme of the Third Army for an attack in mid-November was discussed. Byng wanted the operations at Ypres to continue, to hold German troops in Flanders.{{sfn|Edmonds|1948|pp=345–346}} The [[Battle of Cambrai (1917)|Battle of Cambrai]] began on 20 November, when the British breached the first two parts of the [[Hindenburg Line]], in the first successful mass use of [[tank]]s in a [[combined arms]] operation.{{sfn|Harris|1995|pp=124–125}}

The experience of the failure to contain the British attacks at Ypres and the drastic reduction in areas of the western front which could be considered "quiet", after the tank and artillery surprise at Cambrai, left the OHL with little choice but to return to a strategy of decisive victory in 1918.{{sfn|Sheldon|2009|p=312}} On 24 October, the Austro-German 14th Army, under {{lang|de|''General der Infanterie''}} [[Otto von Below]], attacked the Italian Second Army on the Isonzo, at the [[Battle of Caporetto]] and in 18 days, inflicted casualties of {{nowrap|650,000 men}} and {{nowrap|3,000 guns.}}{{sfn|Miles|1948|p=15}} In fear that Italy might be put out of the war, the French and British Governments offered reinforcements.{{sfn|Bean|1933|pp=935–936}} British and French troops were swiftly moved from {{nowrap|10 November – 12 December}} but the diversion of resources from the BEF forced Haig to conclude the 3rd Battle of Ypres short of [[Westrozebeke]], the last substantial British attack being made on 10 November.{{sfn|Bean|1933|p=936}}

===Casualties===
Various casualty figures have been published, sometimes with acrimony, although the highest estimates for British and German casualties appear to be discredited.{{sfn|McRandle|Quirk|2006|pp=667–701}} In the Official History, Brigadier-General [[James E. Edmonds|J. E. Edmonds]] put British casualties at {{nowrap|244,897}} and wrote that equivalent German figures were not available, estimating German losses at {{nowrap|400,000.}} Edmonds considered that {{nowrap|30 percent needed}} to be added to German statistics, to make them comparable with British casualty criteria.{{sfn|Edmonds|1948|pp=361–363}} In 2007, Sheldon wrote that although German casualties from {{nowrap|1 June – 10 November}} {{nowrap|were 217,194,}} a figure available in Volume III of the {{lang|de|''Sanitätsbericht''}} (1934), Edmonds may not have included them as they did not fit his case. Sheldon recorded {{nowrap|182,396 slightly}} wounded and sick soldiers ''not struck off unit strength'', which if included would make {{nowrap|399,590 German}} losses.{{sfn|Sheldon|2007|pp=313–315}} The British claim to have taken {{nowrap|24,065 prisoners}} has not been disputed.{{sfn|Boraston|1919|p=133}}{{efn|In 1940, [[C. R. M. F. Cruttwell]] recorded {{nowrap|300,000 British}} casualties and {{nowrap|400,000 German.}}{{sfn|Cruttwell|1940|p=442}} Wolff in 1958, gave German casualties as {{nowrap|270,713}} and {{nowrap|448,688 British.}}{{sfn|Wolff|1958|p=259}} In 1959, [[Cyril Falls]] estimated {{nowrap|240,000 British,}} {{nowrap|8,525 French}} and {{nowrap|260,000 German}} casualties.{{sfn|Falls|1959|p=303}} [[John Terraine]] followed Falls in 1963 but did not accept that German losses were as high {{nowrap|as 400,000.}}{{sfn|Terraine|1963|p=372}} [[A. J. P. Taylor]] in 1972, wrote that the Official History had performed a "conjuring trick" on these figures and that no one believed these "farcical calculations". Taylor put British wounded and killed at {{nowrap|300,000 and}} German losses at {{nowrap|200,000.}}{{sfn|Taylor|1972|pp=181–182}} In 1977, Terraine argued that twenty percent needed to be added to the German figures for some lightly wounded men, who would have been included under British definitions of casualties, making German casualties {{circa|260,400.}} Terraine refuted Wolff (1958), who despite writing that {{nowrap|448,614 British}} casualties was the total for the BEF in the second half of 1917, neglected to deduct {{nowrap|75,681 British}} casualties for the [[Battle of Cambrai (1917)|Battle of Cambrai]] given in the ''Official Statistics'', from which he quoted or "normal wastage", averaging {{nowrap|35,000 per}} month in "quiet" periods.{{sfn|Terraine|1977|pp=344–345}} Prior and Wilson in 1997, gave British losses as {{nowrap|275,000 and}} German casualties just {{nowrap|under 200,000.}}{{sfn|Prior|Wilson|1996|p=195}} Hagenlücke in 1997, gave {{circa|217,000 German}} casualties.{{sfn|Liddle|1997|pp=45–58}} Sheffield wrote in 2002, that Holmes's guess of {{nowrap|260,000 casualties}} on both sides seemed about right.{{sfn|Sheffield|2001|p=216}} In 2011, Sheffield did not offer figures for either side, leaving the verdict to [[General von Kuhl]], "The sacrifices that the British made for the Entente were fully justified".{{sfn|Sheffield|2011|pp=248 & 439}}}}

===Commemoration===
[[File:View from top of Tyne Cot.JPG|thumb|{{center|Tyne Cot Commonwealth War Graves Cemetery and Memorial to the Missing}}]]
The [[Menin Gate|Menin Gate Memorial to the Missing]] commemorates those of all Commonwealth nations, except New Zealand, who died in the Ypres Salient and have no known grave. In the case of the United Kingdom only casualties before 16 August 1917 are commemorated on the memorial. United Kingdom and New Zealand servicemen who died after that date are named on the memorial at [[Tyne Cot Cemetery]]. There are numerous tributes and memorials all over Australia and New Zealand to ANZAC soldiers who died in the battle, including plaques at the [[Christchurch]] and [[Dunedin, New Zealand|Dunedin]] railway stations. The Canadian Corps participation in the Second Battle of Passchendaele is commemorated with the [[Passchendaele Memorial]] located at the former site of the Crest Farm on the south-west fringe of Passchendaele village.{{sfn|Vance|1997|p=66}} One of the newest monuments to be dedicated to the fighting contribution of a group is the [[Celtic Cross]] memorial, commemorating the Scottish contributions and efforts in the fighting in Flanders during the Great War. This memorial is located on the Frezenberg Ridge where the Scottish 9th and 15th Divisions, fought during the Battle of Passchendaele. The monument was dedicated by [[Linda Fabiani]], the Minister for Europe of the [[Scottish Parliament]], during the late summer of 2007, the 90th anniversary of the battle.{{sfn|SG|2007|nopp=y}}

